{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613645"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:37:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:37:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16321"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16321"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116146"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9012"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98142"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"},{"type":"tags","id":"8447"},{"type":"tags","id":"9947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21444"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21450"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116146"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tear film that covers and protects the surface of the eye consists of three distinct layers. Each layer has specific functions and origins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the mucin (posterior) layer of tears is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Produced by conjunctival goblet cells","Comprises 98% of tear volume","Forms the outermost layer of tears","Prevents evaporation of tears","Produced by meibomian glands"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econjunctival goblet cells produce the mucin layer\u003C/strong\u003E of tears, which forms the innermost (posterior) layer of the tear film. This layer helps tears adhere to the corneal surface and provides lubrication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe aqueous layer makes up about 98% of tears, not the mucin layer, whilst the lipid layer forms the outermost layer and prevents evaporation of tears. The meibomian glands are responsible for producing the lipid layer rather than the mucin layer. The mucin layer serves several important functions including helping tears adhere to the eye surface, providing lubrication, and trapping debris and pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The tear film consists of three layers: mucin (posterior), aqueous (middle), and lipid (anterior).","The mucin layer is produced by conjunctival goblet cells and helps tears adhere to the eye surface.","The aqueous layer, not the mucin layer, is the main component of tears, comprising about 98% of tear volume."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98142"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16321"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"9